Chicago Bike Share

Urban bike sharing programs have continued to grow over recent years. According to the National Association of City Transportation Officials (NACTO), there were 35 million bikeshare trips in 2017 alone[1]. In Chicago, the bikeshare program is spearheaded citywide by Divvy. In 2016, Divvy installed an additional 100 bike stations resulting in over 10.7 million trips. Divvy reports that these 10.7 million trips amounted to over 20 million miles ridden, 13.8 million pounds of reduced CO2, and over 800 thousand gallons of gasoline saved[2]. Let’s take a look at Divvy’s role in Chicago being named the number one city for biking by Bicycling Magazine in 2016 [diff ref].

The Data

The data used in this analysis was obtained from Divvy’s System Data portal, accessible here The data available is at the trip level, documenting the following characteristics of each ride[3]:

  • Trip start day and time
  • Trip end day and time
  • Trip start station
  • Trip end station
  • Rider type (Member, Single Ride, and Explore Pass)
  • If a Member trip, it will also include Member’s gender and year of birth

Additionally, Divvy provides a separate location data file detailing the longitude and latitude coordinates and bike capacity of each bike station. To prepare the data for analysis, these files will need to be joined to include location information for the origin and destination of each trip. The datasets obtained from the raw data are named as follows:

  • trips_Q1 : Divvy trips during Q1 of 2016
  • trips_Q2_04 : Divvy trips during April of 2016
  • trips_Q2_05 : Divvy trips during May of 2016
  • trips_Q2_06 : Divvy trips during June of 2016
  • trips_Q3 : Divvy trips during Q3 of 2016
  • trips_Q4 : Divvy trips during Q4 of 2016
  • stations_Q1Q2 : Divvy station locations for Q1 and Q2 of 2016
  • stations_Q3 : Divvy station locations for Q3 of 2016
  • stations_Q4 : Divvy station locations for Q4 of 2016

At the end of the joining process, we will have two datasets: trips_2016 and stations_2016, holding their respective information.

trips_2016 <- data.frame(pos=rownames(trips_2016),word=trips_2016,row.names = NULL)

In joining the datasets, we need to keep in mind that during 2016 Divvy added 100 new bike stations. Logically, the Q4 station dataset would have all of the stations, new and old. However, we do not know if Divvy also removed stations. To account for this possibility, we need to merge the station datasets to ensure all bike stations are included.

# for the first merge, use the 'all.y' option to ensure that all stations in the Q3 set are included as there are more than in Q1 and Q2. Use the 'all.x' option to make sure that all Q1Q2 stations are included, just in case some were removed.
stations_2016 <- merge(stations_Q1Q2, stations_Q3, all.y = TRUE, by = "id", suffixes = c("Q1Q2","Q3"))
stations_2016 <- merge(stations_2016, stations_Q4, by = "id",all.y = TRUE, all.x = TRUE, suffixes = c("Q4",""))

For kicks, let’s check to see if any stations were removed in 2016. Here, the dplyr package will be used to create a custom function to check inclusion.

library(dplyr)
contains <- function(x, y) {
  removed <- list()
  for (i in 1:length(x)){
    if (!(x[i] %in% y)){
      removed <- c(remove,x[i])
    }
  }
  removed
}
Q1Q2_station_ids <- unlist(stations_Q1Q2["id"])
Q3_station_ids <- unlist(stations_Q3["id"])
Q4_station_ids <- unlist(stations_Q4["id"])

The function above will return the string, “Contained” if all elements of the first list are contained in the second list.

# Q1Q2 is contained by Q3
contains(Q1Q2_station_ids, Q3_station_ids)
[1] "Contained"
# Q1Q2 is contained by Q4
contains(Q1Q2_station_ids, Q4_station_ids)
[1] "Contained"
# Q3 is contained by Q4
contains(Q3_station_ids, Q4_station_ids)
[1] "Contained"

This confirms that Divvy bike stations were only added, none were removed. Here’s what our station data looks like:

Notice that there are duplicate columns for each dataset that was merged. Normally, this is redundant. However, because Divvy stations went through some change in 2016 it is worthwhile to check that the characteristics of each station remain the same. Divvy could have moved, expanded, or renamed stations! This is relevant information for a concerned data scientist.

Let’s see if anything changed over the course of the year. First we’ll check to ensure that station locations haven’t changed. The dataset below contains only stations that have the same latitude and longitude for the entire year.

stations_2016[which((stations_2016$latitudeQ1Q2 = stations_2016$latitudeQ3) & (stations_2016$latitudeQ3 = stations_2016$latitude) & (stations_2016$longitudeQ1Q2 = stations_2016$longitudeQ3) & (stations_2016$longitudeQ3 = stations_2016$longitude)),]

Fortunately, none of the 2016 Divvy bike stations physically moved after installation. Below, we see the same for Divvy station capacity.

stations_2016[which((stations_2016$dpcapacityQ1Q2 = stations_2016$dpcapacityQ3) & (stations_2016$dpcapacityQ3 = stations_2016$dpcapacity)),]

While no stations were removed, relocated, or expanded, some stations were renamed! This could cause some confusion later, let’s take a look at stations with new names.

stations_2016$nameQ1Q2 <- as.character(stations_2016$nameQ1Q2)
stations_2016$nameQ3 <- as.character(stations_2016$nameQ3)
stations_2016$name <- as.character(stations_2016$name)
stations_2016[which((stations_2016$nameQ1Q2 == stations_2016$nameQ3) & (stations_2016$nameQ3 == stations_2016$name)),]
